235
00:19:50,273 --> 00:19:51,900
You'd be here till Monday!

236
00:19:53,193 --> 00:19:55,070
Get moving, spastic!

237
00:19:55,153 --> 00:19:57,197
She hasn't got all day!

238
00:20:01,159 --> 00:20:05,955
Go see my mother.
She has an elephant's memory.

239
00:20:06,039 --> 00:20:07,123
Elephant mom!

240
00:20:09,417 --> 00:20:10,960
Thank you.

241
00:20:29,479 --> 00:20:30,730
Bredoteau.

242
00:20:32,774 --> 00:20:35,026
- Pardon?
- The name you're after.

243
00:20:35,110 --> 00:20:39,614
But if I say it, it won't count.
I'm senile.

244
00:20:39,697 --> 00:20:41,574
Ignore him. He's senile.

245
00:20:41,658 --> 00:20:44,285
See what he's done to my laurel?

246
00:20:48,915 --> 00:20:51,543
His old job was punching metro tickets.

247
00:20:51,626 --> 00:20:54,587
Now he gets up every night...

248
00:20:54,671 --> 00:20:57,424
to punch holes in my laurel!

249
00:20:57,507 --> 00:21:00,343
Too bad it's not hardy.

250
00:21:00,427 --> 00:21:03,555
We all need a way to relax.

251
00:21:03,638 --> 00:21:05,557
- I skip stones.
- You do?

252
00:21:05,640 --> 00:21:09,060
I'll find it, don't worry.
I'm very organized.

253
00:21:09,144 --> 00:21:12,063
- I like everything.
- Like what?

254
00:21:12,147 --> 00:21:14,315
Your son's nearly fifty...

255
00:21:14,399 --> 00:21:16,901
and I'm still doing his bookkeeping!

256
00:21:16,985 --> 00:21:20,613
You were still squeezing
his toothpaste at fifteen.

257
00:21:20,697 --> 00:21:23,575
- It follows.
- Camus...

258
00:21:23,658 --> 00:21:28,121
second floor, Broussard was on B block...

259
00:21:28,204 --> 00:21:29,747
Got it!

260
00:21:29,831 --> 00:21:31,958
Bredoteau, fifth floor.

261
00:21:32,792 --> 00:21:34,627
They were northerners.

262
00:21:34,711 --> 00:21:36,629
Bredoteau.

263
00:21:36,713 --> 00:21:38,381
What more I can say?

264
00:21:41,676 --> 00:21:46,806
<i>How could I live</i>

265
00:21:46,890 --> 00:21:56,316
<i>Never to know the joy that you give</i>

266
00:21:56,399 --> 00:22:00,820
<i>When I'm in your arms</i>

267
00:22:00,904 --> 00:22:07,076
<i>I'm under your charms</i>

268
00:22:07,160 --> 00:22:14,501
<i>How could I live</i>

269
00:22:14,584 --> 00:22:20,715
<i>Without you</i>

270
00:22:42,070 --> 00:22:43,821
<i>Groping under the photo booth...</i>

271
00:22:43,905 --> 00:22:45,865
<i>is Nino Quincampoix.</i>

272
00:22:50,036 --> 00:22:54,958
<i>When Amélie lacked playmates,
Nino had too many.</i>

273
00:23:06,135 --> 00:23:08,888
<i>Five miles apart, they both dreamed...</i>

274
00:23:08,972 --> 00:23:11,182
<i>of having a brother and sister...</i>

275
00:23:11,266 --> 00:23:13,685
<i>to be with all the time.</i>

276
00:23:34,664 --> 00:23:36,165
Hi, Dad.

277
00:23:37,417 --> 00:23:39,711
A new friend?

278
00:23:39,794 --> 00:23:42,255
I've had him for years.

279
00:23:42,338 --> 00:23:46,551
Your mother hated him,
so he lived in the tool shed.

280
00:23:46,634 --> 00:23:49,262
There. Let's reconcile them.

281
00:23:52,473 --> 00:23:55,143
There. How about that?

282
00:23:58,479 --> 00:24:03,860
Dad, if you found a precious relic
from your childhood...

283
00:24:03,943 --> 00:24:05,570
how would you feel?

284
00:24:05,653 --> 00:24:08,698
Happy? Sad? Nostalgic?

285
00:24:08,781 --> 00:24:11,409
This gnome isn't a relic.

286
00:24:11,492 --> 00:24:15,371
He was a retirement gift
from my old regiment.

287
00:24:15,455 --> 00:24:20,960
No, I mean something you hid,
like a secret treasure.

288
00:24:21,044 --> 00:24:24,130
I should varnish him before the autumn.

289
00:24:27,008 --> 00:24:29,927
I'll make some tea.
You want some?

290
00:24:30,011 --> 00:24:32,305
Breathe in. Hold still.

291
00:24:33,890 --> 00:24:36,017
Better now?

292
00:24:36,100 --> 00:24:39,854
Shut the door!
There's a howling gale.

293
00:24:39,937 --> 00:24:41,898
It's not Siberia.

294
00:24:41,981 --> 00:24:45,485
You're not allergic to car fumes!

295
00:24:45,568 --> 00:24:48,655
I almost coughed up my pleura last night.

296
00:24:48,738 --> 00:24:50,657
Cough up a pleura?

297
00:24:50,740 --> 00:24:54,410
- What's on today, Suzanne?
- Endives au gratin.

298
00:24:54,494 --> 00:24:56,913
They'll have you on your knees.

299
00:24:56,996 --> 00:24:58,956
- That's good?
- Depends where you fall.

300
00:24:59,040 --> 00:25:01,751
- If in front of the toilet...
- Not good.

301
00:25:07,131 --> 00:25:11,260
12:15, laughs orgasmically
to attract alpha male.

302
00:25:11,844 --> 00:25:13,638
He's gonna drive me berserk.

303
00:25:13,721 --> 00:25:15,765
Can't he give up?

304
00:25:15,848 --> 00:25:17,642
There are plenty of other bars!

305
00:25:17,725 --> 00:25:19,727
Good-bye.

306
00:25:19,811 --> 00:25:20,812
Madame Suzanne?

307
00:25:20,895 --> 00:25:22,230
Madame Suzanne?

308
00:25:22,730 --> 00:25:26,067
Au gratin means white sauce, right?

309
00:25:26,734 --> 00:25:27,735
Yes. Why?

310
00:25:27,819 --> 00:25:32,824
I can't stomach it,
like you and horse meat.

311
00:25:32,907 --> 00:25:36,494
It's not my stomach, it's my memory.

312
00:25:36,577 --> 00:25:38,454
I'd rather cook human flesh.

313
00:25:39,038 --> 00:25:40,581
You're kidding.

314
00:25:52,176 --> 00:25:56,097
Madame Suzanne, can I leave early today?

315
00:25:56,764 --> 00:25:58,141
What's his name?

316
00:25:58,224 --> 00:26:00,143
Dominique Bredoteau.

317
00:26:06,649 --> 00:26:07,650
Hello.

318
00:26:09,235 --> 00:26:12,113
- You're Dominique Bredoteau?
- That's me.

319
00:26:12,780 --> 00:26:15,074
Why?

320
00:26:15,158 --> 00:26:18,578
It's about the petition.

321
00:26:18,661 --> 00:26:20,079
Petition?

322
00:26:20,621 --> 00:26:24,834
Yes. The petition to...

323
00:26:26,294 --> 00:26:28,171
to canonize Lady Di!

324
00:26:28,254 --> 00:26:29,881
No, thanks.

325
00:26:29,964 --> 00:26:31,716
No.

326
00:26:38,806 --> 00:26:41,350
Ladies and gentlemen,
sorry to bother you...

327
00:26:46,105 --> 00:26:47,982
- Yes?
- Hello.

328
00:26:48,065 --> 00:26:53,154
I'm looking for Dominique Bredoteau
for the European census.

329
00:26:53,237 --> 00:26:55,490
Come up, third floor.

330
00:27:05,583 --> 00:27:07,168
Hello, kitten.

331
00:27:10,004 --> 00:27:12,632
Earl Grey? Jasmine?

332
00:27:14,717 --> 00:27:16,636
What will you have?

333
00:27:20,431 --> 00:27:21,974
I'm busy.

334
00:27:30,775 --> 00:27:32,527
Here.

335
00:27:32,610 --> 00:27:33,653
Coming!

336
00:27:34,987 --> 00:27:37,532
Where can I find Dominique Bredoteau?

337
00:27:38,866 --> 00:27:43,204
Poor dear! You just missed him.

338
00:27:43,287 --> 00:27:46,207
Look, there he goes now.

339
00:27:55,883 --> 00:27:56,926
Bretod-eau.

340
00:27:57,969 --> 00:27:59,887
Not Bredot-eau.

341
00:28:00,930 --> 00:28:05,101
You need a little mulled wine.

342
00:28:05,184 --> 00:28:06,185
Come in.

343
00:28:11,399 --> 00:28:15,987
I've lived here for five years.
I never saw you before.

344
00:28:16,070 --> 00:28:18,823
I never go out on the landing.

345
00:28:18,906 --> 00:28:22,660
I'm fussy about who I meet.

346
00:28:22,743 --> 00:28:24,704
They're all bums.

347
00:28:26,747 --> 00:28:29,166
Come in.

348
00:28:31,794 --> 00:28:34,672
They call me the Glass Man...

349
00:28:34,755 --> 00:28:38,134
but my name is Raymond Dufayel.

350
00:28:39,260 --> 00:28:41,262
Amélie Poulain. I'm a waitress at...

351
00:28:41,345 --> 00:28:44,265
The Two Windmills. I know.

352
00:28:44,348 --> 00:28:50,855
And right now,
your Bredoteau basket is empty.

353
00:28:50,938 --> 00:28:54,442
Because it's not do. It's to.

354
00:28:54,525 --> 00:28:56,110
Like Toto.

355
00:29:01,073 --> 00:29:02,533
I love that painting.

356
00:29:02,617 --> 00:29:05,620
It's the Luncheon of the Boating Party.

357
00:29:07,079 --> 00:29:08,080
By Renoir.

358
00:29:14,211 --> 00:29:17,840
I've painted one each year
for twenty years.

359
00:29:19,800 --> 00:29:22,178
The hardest part is the looks.

360
00:29:22,261 --> 00:29:23,512
I sometimes feel like...

361
00:29:23,596 --> 00:29:28,309
they deliberately change
their mood behind my back.

362
00:29:28,392 --> 00:29:30,227
They look quite happy.

363
00:29:30,311 --> 00:29:32,229
They should be!

364
00:29:32,313 --> 00:29:35,399
They're eating hare with morels...

365
00:29:35,483 --> 00:29:39,320
and waffles with jam for the kids.

366
00:29:40,404 --> 00:29:45,326
Now, where's that piece of paper?

367
00:29:47,161 --> 00:29:51,874
You've noticed my video camera.

368
00:29:51,958 --> 00:29:55,086
A gift from my sister-in-law.

369
00:29:55,169 --> 00:29:58,089
I put it there...

370
00:29:58,172 --> 00:30:02,218
so I don't need to wind up my clocks.

371
00:30:02,301 --> 00:30:05,096
After all these years...

372
00:30:05,179 --> 00:30:09,433
the only person I still can't capture...

373
00:30:09,517 --> 00:30:12,520
is the girl with the glass of water.

374
00:30:12,603 --> 00:30:16,190
She's in the middle, yet she's outside.

375
00:30:17,525 --> 00:30:19,652
Maybe she's just different.

376
00:30:21,529 --> 00:30:23,239
In what way?

377
00:30:24,615 --> 00:30:26,325
I don't know.

378
00:30:27,201 --> 00:30:32,206
When she was little,
she rarely played with other kids.

379
00:30:33,207 --> 00:30:35,710
Maybe never.

380
00:30:39,088 --> 00:30:40,464
Dominique...

381
00:30:40,548 --> 00:30:45,094
Dominique Bretodeau, 27 Rue Mouffetard.

382
00:30:46,679 --> 00:30:48,347
It's for you.

383
00:30:48,597 --> 00:30:50,266
<i>Every Tuesday morning...</i>

384
00:30:50,349 --> 00:30:53,477
<i>Dominique Bretodeau buys a chicken.</i>

385
00:30:53,561 --> 00:30:56,731
<i>He roasts it with potatoes.</i>

386
00:30:57,314 --> 00:31:00,067
<i>After carving the legs and wings...</i>

387
00:31:00,151 --> 00:31:04,238
<i>he loves picking the hot carcass
with his fingers...</i>

388
00:31:04,321 --> 00:31:06,490
<i>starting with the oysters.</i>

389
00:31:09,076 --> 00:31:13,164
<i>But not today.
Bretodeau won't buy a chicken.</i>

390
00:31:13,247 --> 00:31:16,625
<i>He'll go no further
than this phone booth here.</i>

391
00:32:26,403 --> 00:32:29,824
<i>In a flash, it all came back.</i>

392
00:32:30,324 --> 00:32:33,035
<i>Bahamontes winning the Tour de France.</i>

393
00:32:36,080 --> 00:32:38,332
<i>Aunt Josette's slips.</i>

394
00:32:40,584 --> 00:32:43,170
<i>And most of all, the tragic day...</i>

395
00:32:45,172 --> 00:32:48,801
<i>The day he won all the marbles.</i>

396
00:33:10,364 --> 00:33:12,616
The pinch, Bretodeau!

397
00:33:12,700 --> 00:33:14,869
Bretodeau, does he know what it is?

398
00:33:22,543 --> 00:33:24,128
Cognac, please.

399
00:33:30,050 --> 00:33:32,052
Amazing, what just happened.

400
00:33:32,136 --> 00:33:34,680
It must be my guardian angel.

401
00:33:36,390 --> 00:33:39,768
The phone booth was calling me...

402
00:33:43,397 --> 00:33:46,859
Same here!
The microwave's calling me.

403
00:33:49,695 --> 00:33:51,363
I'll have another cognac.

404
00:34:00,748 --> 00:34:02,541
Life's funny.

405
00:34:04,210 --> 00:34:08,589
To a kid, time always drags.
Suddenly you're fifty.

406
00:34:11,592 --> 00:34:16,263
All that's left of your childhood
fits in a rusty little box.

407
00:34:20,601 --> 00:34:22,686
You got kids, Miss?

408
00:34:27,274 --> 00:34:29,777
I have a daughter about your age.

409
00:34:33,572 --> 00:34:36,659
We haven't spoken for years.

410
00:34:36,742 --> 00:34:40,704
I heard she had a child, a boy.

411
00:34:40,788 --> 00:34:42,665
His name is Lucas.

412
00:34:48,545 --> 00:34:53,133
It's time I looked them up,
before I'm in a box myself.

413
00:34:54,468 --> 00:34:55,719
Don't you think?

414
00:35:03,978 --> 00:35:07,898
<i>Amélie has a strange feeling
of absolute harmony.</i>

415
00:35:07,982 --> 00:35:09,650
<i>It's a perfect moment.</i>

416
00:35:09,733 --> 00:35:11,026
<i>Soft light...</i>

417
00:35:11,110 --> 00:35:14,363
<i>a scent in the air,
the quiet murmur of the city.</i>

418
00:35:15,155 --> 00:35:17,783
<i>She breathes deeply.
Life is simple and clear.</i>

419
00:35:17,866 --> 00:35:23,289
<i>A surge of love, an urge
to help mankind comes over her.</i>

420
00:35:35,843 --> 00:35:39,430
Let me help you.
Step down. Here we go!

421
00:35:39,513 --> 00:35:41,348
The drum major's widow!

422
00:35:41,432 --> 00:35:43,809
She's worn his coat since the day he died.

423
00:35:44,810 --> 00:35:47,438
The horse's head has lost an ear!

424
00:35:47,521 --> 00:35:51,150
That's the florist laughing.
He has crinkly eyes.

425
00:35:51,233 --> 00:35:54,320
In the bakery window, lollipops.

426
00:35:54,862 --> 00:35:58,699
Smell that!
They're giving out melon slices.

427
00:36:00,326 --> 00:36:02,536
Sugarplum ice cream!

428
00:36:02,619 --> 00:36:04,288
We're passing the park butcher.

429
00:36:04,371 --> 00:36:07,708
Ham, 79 francs. Spareribs, 45!

430
00:36:07,791 --> 00:36:12,588
Now the cheese shop.
Picadors are 12.90. Cabecaus 23.50.

431
00:36:12,671 --> 00:36:17,217
A baby's watching a dog
that's watching the chickens.

432
00:36:17,301 --> 00:36:20,471
Now we're at the kiosk by the metro.

433
00:36:20,554 --> 00:36:22,681
I'll leave you here. Bye!

434
00:37:14,108 --> 00:37:17,319
She can't relate to other people.

435
00:37:18,737 --> 00:37:21,657
She was always a lonely child.

436
00:37:24,451 --> 00:37:27,496
On a sparkling evening in July...

437
00:37:27,579 --> 00:37:32,876
while on the beaches, holiday hordes
relax in the new-found sun...

438
00:37:32,960 --> 00:37:35,671
and Paris's sweltering denizens...

439
00:37:35,754 --> 00:37:40,008
gaze at the star bursts
of the traditional fireworks...

440
00:37:40,092 --> 00:37:41,343
Amélie Poulain...

441
00:37:41,427 --> 00:37:46,807
Godmother of Outcasts,
Madonna of the Unloved...

442
00:37:46,890 --> 00:37:49,435
finally succumbed to exhaustion.

443
00:37:50,310 --> 00:37:54,189
In Paris's stricken streets...

444
00:37:54,273 --> 00:37:56,024
a countless throng of mourners...

445
00:37:56,108 --> 00:38:00,237
lined her funeral route in silence...

446
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:05,576
with the measureless grief
of newly orphaned children.

447
00:38:05,659 --> 00:38:09,913
What a strange destiny
for one who gave her all...

448
00:38:09,997 --> 00:38:13,750
yet took such joy
in life's simple pleasures.

449
00:38:13,834 --> 00:38:15,085
GLOBAL HUMANITARIAN
RELIEF INITIATIVE

450
00:38:15,169 --> 00:38:18,547
Like Don Quixote, she pitted herself...

451
00:38:18,630 --> 00:38:23,177
against the grinding windmills
of all life's miseries.

452
00:38:27,306 --> 00:38:28,682
WINTER IN SWITZERLAND

453
00:38:34,188 --> 00:38:38,275
It was a losing battle
that claimed her life too soon.

454
00:38:38,358 --> 00:38:44,531
At barely 23, Amélie Poulain
let her young, tired body merge...

455
00:38:44,615 --> 00:38:48,035
with the ebb and flow of universal woe.

456
00:38:49,536 --> 00:38:52,080
As she went, she felt a stab of regret...

457
00:38:52,164 --> 00:38:54,291
for letting her father die...

458
00:38:54,374 --> 00:38:58,795
without trying to give his stifled life...

459
00:38:58,879 --> 00:39:04,092
the breath of air she had given
to so many others.

460
00:41:20,520 --> 00:41:21,521
Wait!

461
00:41:26,526 --> 00:41:28,028
Wait!

462
00:41:31,365 --> 00:41:32,407
Wait!

463
00:41:33,575 --> 00:41:35,535
Wait! Wait! Wait!

464
00:41:37,704 --> 00:41:39,498
Wait! Wait!

465
00:42:21,415 --> 00:42:23,417
<i>Pages full of dual ID photos...</i>

466
00:42:23,500 --> 00:42:26,962
<i>torn up and discarded by their owners...</i>

467
00:42:27,045 --> 00:42:30,549
<i>carefully reassembled by some oddball.</i>

468
00:42:31,925 --> 00:42:34,094
<i>Some family album!</i>

469
00:42:37,723 --> 00:42:39,391
A pack of Gaulaises.

470
00:42:39,474 --> 00:42:42,686
Just a second.
It's so smoky in here.

471
00:42:42,769 --> 00:42:45,355
Where are they?
I can't see a thing.

472
00:42:45,439 --> 00:42:48,024
More to the left. More...

473
00:42:51,945 --> 00:42:54,030
You need change.

474
00:42:54,114 --> 00:42:55,615
Forget it.

475
00:42:57,784 --> 00:43:00,036
A mauresque for the young man.

476
00:43:00,120 --> 00:43:03,707
One kir, one mauresque,
and two mint sodas.

477
00:43:03,790 --> 00:43:06,877
Was that prenuptial or post-smooching?

478
00:43:06,960 --> 00:43:09,296
Are you a congenital schmuck?

479
00:43:11,089 --> 00:43:12,048
Prenuptial.

480
00:43:12,132 --> 00:43:15,469
Don't worry.
You'll find your Mr. Right one day.

481
00:43:16,344 --> 00:43:19,681
All women want to sleep
on a man's shoulder.

482
00:43:19,765 --> 00:43:23,059
All men snore after a few drinks...

483
00:43:23,143 --> 00:43:25,020
and I have a musical ear.

484
00:43:25,103 --> 00:43:27,481
I had my nasal cavities fixed.

485
00:43:27,564 --> 00:43:30,525
I see you're a born romantic.

486
00:43:32,486 --> 00:43:35,113
I see you've never known true love.

487
00:43:36,364 --> 00:43:38,992
I did. It shortened my leg.

488
00:43:40,535 --> 00:43:43,246
I thought you fell off a horse.

489
00:43:43,330 --> 00:43:44,998
I did.

490
00:43:45,081 --> 00:43:47,417
I was in love with a trapeze artist.

491
00:43:47,501 --> 00:43:50,921
Stupid me. They always
drop you at the last minute.

492
00:43:51,004 --> 00:43:54,424
He dropped me just before my act.

493
00:43:55,634 --> 00:43:57,219
It floored me.

494
00:43:57,302 --> 00:43:59,346
Plus the horse...

495
00:44:00,138 --> 00:44:02,474
with me under it.

496
00:44:05,519 --> 00:44:06,728
The mauresque?

497
00:44:06,812 --> 00:44:09,689
Still, true love does exist.

498
00:44:09,773 --> 00:44:11,566
I know.

499
00:44:11,650 --> 00:44:13,693
After 30 years behind a bar...

500
00:44:13,777 --> 00:44:15,278
I'm an expert.

501
00:44:15,362 --> 00:44:17,405
I'll even give you the recipe.

502
00:44:20,200 --> 00:44:22,619
Take two regulars...

503
00:44:22,702 --> 00:44:25,831
mix them together and let them stew.

504
00:44:25,914 --> 00:44:27,833
It never fails.

505
00:44:36,466 --> 00:44:37,926
Excuse me!

506
00:44:39,052 --> 00:44:41,555
- Excuse me!
- I'll go.

507
00:44:45,225 --> 00:44:47,352
Haven't you hurt enough people?

508
00:44:51,147 --> 00:44:52,774
Gina can defend herself.

509
00:44:52,858 --> 00:44:55,151
I don't mean Gina.

510
00:44:55,235 --> 00:44:56,736
I mean Georgette.

511
00:45:00,407 --> 00:45:01,867
Look!

512
00:45:01,950 --> 00:45:05,579
She craves your attention,
but all you can see is Gina.

513
00:45:08,081 --> 00:45:09,583
Poor girl!

514
00:45:09,666 --> 00:45:12,669
The things she does
to catch your eye!

515
00:45:15,505 --> 00:45:18,049
You really must be blind.

516
00:45:26,349 --> 00:45:28,435
I'm off on a date. Bye!

517
00:45:32,647 --> 00:45:35,233
Whoever her new one is...

518
00:45:35,317 --> 00:45:39,279
he can't be worse
than that nut with his tape recorder.

519
00:45:39,946 --> 00:45:42,699
Joseph's not so nutty.

520
00:45:42,782 --> 00:45:44,618
He's just in pain.

521
00:45:44,701 --> 00:45:47,579
Come on!
They split up two months ago.

522
00:45:47,662 --> 00:45:51,124
To keep on coming here,
he must be a masochist.

523
00:45:52,292 --> 00:45:54,544
Don't say you haven't noticed.

524
00:45:55,670 --> 00:45:57,130
Noticed what?

525
00:45:57,213 --> 00:46:00,300
Well, he always sits here, right?

526
00:46:00,383 --> 00:46:01,468
At number 8?

527
00:46:01,551 --> 00:46:02,719
Sit down.

528
00:46:04,054 --> 00:46:05,513
Sit down, Georgette.

529
00:46:07,223 --> 00:46:09,225
What can you see?

530
00:46:09,309 --> 00:46:11,561
My cigarette counter.

531
00:46:11,645 --> 00:46:13,980
Nothing's missing?

532
00:46:14,064 --> 00:46:15,273
Well, no.

533
00:46:16,316 --> 00:46:17,817
Make an effort.

534
00:46:24,658 --> 00:46:27,494
I can't see what!

535
00:46:27,577 --> 00:46:30,246
Think about it. Good night.

536
00:46:49,933 --> 00:46:53,395
<i>Letter Arrives 30 Years Late.</i>

537
00:46:53,979 --> 00:46:58,316
<i>A mailbag found by climbers
on a glacier on Mont Blanc...</i>

538
00:46:58,400 --> 00:47:03,613
<i>was part of a cargo lost
in a plane crash in the late 1960s.</i>

539
00:47:04,823 --> 00:47:08,284
So sad.
A young, pretty princess for once.

540
00:47:08,368 --> 00:47:10,745
It's OK if she's old and ugly?

541
00:47:10,829 --> 00:47:13,039
Sure! Look at Mother Teresa.

542
00:47:14,916 --> 00:47:17,419
Is he still chasing Gina?

543
00:47:18,628 --> 00:47:21,214
No, he has somebody else.

544
00:47:21,297 --> 00:47:23,508
Anyone I know?

545
00:47:24,217 --> 00:47:26,594
Funny about this glacier...

546
00:47:26,678 --> 00:47:28,596
Somebody at the Two Windmills?

547
00:47:30,557 --> 00:47:31,725
Not you!

548
00:47:34,561 --> 00:47:36,938
Not Suzanne...

549
00:47:38,314 --> 00:47:40,734
- No!
- Yes.

550
00:47:44,237 --> 00:47:45,613
There he is again.

551
00:47:45,697 --> 00:47:47,907
How strange.

552
00:47:48,742 --> 00:47:51,327
- And here.
- Him again!

553
00:47:51,411 --> 00:47:52,954
Lyon Station.

554
00:47:54,748 --> 00:47:57,584
And here.
March 5, Austerlitz.

555
00:47:58,168 --> 00:48:01,588
Always the same blank face.
Always neutral.

556
00:48:02,839 --> 00:48:04,132
Twelve times.

557
00:48:04,758 --> 00:48:06,259
I counted.

558
00:48:07,260 --> 00:48:08,511
It's very odd.

559
00:48:08,595 --> 00:48:12,223
Why keep taking your picture
all over town...

560
00:48:12,307 --> 00:48:14,225
and throw them away?

561
00:48:14,309 --> 00:48:16,436
Good one too.

562
00:48:17,312 --> 00:48:18,772
It's like a ritual.

563
00:48:18,855 --> 00:48:22,484
He's probably terrified of growing old.

564
00:48:22,567 --> 00:48:24,986
It's his only consolation.

565
00:48:26,696 --> 00:48:28,114
He's dead!

566
00:48:30,492 --> 00:48:33,286
He's scared of being forgotten.

567
00:48:34,079 --> 00:48:37,582
He wants to remind people of his face.

568
00:48:38,166 --> 00:48:41,294
Like faxing his portrait
from the afterlife.

569
00:48:41,377 --> 00:48:46,382
A dead man scared of being forgotten.

570
00:48:46,466 --> 00:48:49,302
These guys here have it made!

571
00:48:49,385 --> 00:48:51,471
They're long dead...

572
00:48:51,554 --> 00:48:55,475
but they'll never be forgotten.

573
00:48:57,727 --> 00:48:59,354
The girl with the glass...

574
00:49:00,271 --> 00:49:03,650
Maybe her thoughts are with somebody else.

575
00:49:03,733 --> 00:49:05,652
Somebody in the picture?

576
00:49:08,363 --> 00:49:11,032
More likely a boy she saw somewhere...

577
00:49:11,699 --> 00:49:14,494
and felt an affinity with.

578
00:49:14,577 --> 00:49:20,708
You mean she'd rather imagine herself
relating to an absent person...

579
00:49:20,792 --> 00:49:25,505
than build relationships
with those around her?

580
00:49:29,217 --> 00:49:33,304
Maybe she tries hard
to fix other people's messy lives.

581
00:49:34,514 --> 00:49:35,849
What about her?

582
00:49:35,932 --> 00:49:38,393
Her own messy life?

583
00:49:40,103 --> 00:49:41,855
Who'll fix that?

584
00:49:43,523 --> 00:49:48,153
It's better to help people
than a garden gnome.

585
00:50:58,848 --> 00:51:04,062
The trucker had 2.8 grams
of alcohol in his blood!

586
00:51:04,145 --> 00:51:05,521
Makes me sick.

587
00:51:05,605 --> 00:51:08,608
Talk about employing irresponsible morons!

588
00:51:09,984 --> 00:51:11,778
- Your keys.
- Hold on, Mello.

589
00:51:11,861 --> 00:51:13,947
Speed kills nowadays.

590
00:51:14,030 --> 00:51:16,366
Model yourself on Lucien.

591
00:51:16,449 --> 00:51:20,119
No radar will ever catch him
while he's working!

592
00:51:20,203 --> 00:51:22,664
Shame on you, Mr. Collignon.

593
00:51:22,747 --> 00:51:24,624
It's not his fault.

594
00:51:24,707 --> 00:51:26,417
True, Mrs. Couchoix.

595
00:51:26,501 --> 00:51:29,170
It's not his fault he can't sleep.

596
00:51:29,254 --> 00:51:30,463
It's Lady Di's.

597
00:51:32,632 --> 00:51:34,759
Guess what I found in the truck?

598
00:51:34,842 --> 00:51:37,178
A lingerie catalog.

599
00:51:37,262 --> 00:51:40,640
He'd pasted Lady Di's face
over the model's!

600
00:51:42,558 --> 00:51:46,813
What today? Five asparagus
or more local history?

601
00:51:47,605 --> 00:51:49,190
Nothing.

602
00:51:57,699 --> 00:52:00,034
KEYS CUT WHILE YOU WAIT

603
00:52:13,965 --> 00:52:15,925
The migraine's better?

604
00:52:16,009 --> 00:52:19,887
Yes, but my sciatica
kept me awake all night.

605
00:52:19,971 --> 00:52:23,850
- It's ages since I saw you looking so good.
- Oh, yeah?

606
00:52:24,767 --> 00:52:29,022
A woman without love wilts
like a flower without sun.

607
00:52:34,861 --> 00:52:36,612
Strange weather today!

608
00:52:37,155 --> 00:52:39,073
What's so funny?

609
00:52:39,157 --> 00:52:41,659
You're only the 100th one to say it.

610
00:52:41,743 --> 00:52:44,662
We pass the time of day
to forget how time passes.

611
00:52:44,746 --> 00:52:48,082
We do it to keep from taking crap.

612
00:52:48,166 --> 00:52:50,793
I write crap that nobody publishes.

613
00:52:50,877 --> 00:52:53,421
- Another rejection?
- My 30th!

614
00:52:53,504 --> 00:52:56,090
Isn't your cousin a book critic?

615
00:52:56,174 --> 00:52:57,717
Forget it!

616
00:52:57,800 --> 00:53:02,347
Critics are like leeches,
sucking the blood of writers.

617
00:53:02,430 --> 00:53:04,265
Is your book...

618
00:53:04,766 --> 00:53:06,559
a love story?

619
00:53:06,642 --> 00:53:09,020
It's about a guy who keeps a journal.

620
00:53:09,103 --> 00:53:11,397
Not about his past...

621
00:53:11,481 --> 00:53:14,233
but about disasters in his future.

622
00:53:14,317 --> 00:53:17,737
So he gets depressed and does nothing.

623
00:53:17,820 --> 00:53:19,614
Basically, it's about a loafer.

624
00:53:20,948 --> 00:53:23,785
I'll dedicate the manuscript to you.

625
00:53:23,868 --> 00:53:27,705
So you'll write off his tab.

626
00:53:27,789 --> 00:53:31,918
His scribbles for my nibbles.
That's sponsorship.

627
00:53:37,924 --> 00:53:40,760
What took you so long?

628
00:53:40,843 --> 00:53:42,387
Look at the time!

629
00:53:44,013 --> 00:53:46,516
Somebody peed in his mother!

630
00:54:36,732 --> 00:54:38,818
FOOT CREAM

631
00:54:44,157 --> 00:54:46,159
TOOTH PASTE

632
00:55:46,928 --> 00:55:49,472
